Clay jars are the watershed between nomadic hunter gatherer and the agrarian then urban march to civilization. The ability to warehouse water, seed or btu&#39;s or KwH&#39;s for a time of future need have been the currency that buys creative human expression in all its forms.

&nbsp;

By boiling this jar one can reclaim both wax and clay for larger and more refined applications. The waxed clay can be composted, effecting a soil remediation through the nutritive content of the beeswax.

&nbsp;

For the exhibition in Hillsborough I delivered this jar the 12 miles to the gallery by boat on the Eno River and its tributaries, and foot, carrying the boat over land for 3 miles from my studio to reach the nearest marginally navigable waterway, Crabtree Creek. My meditative intent was to carry the weight of that watershed moment in which our predecessors first achieved warehousing of surplus and its subsequent urbanity.

&nbsp;

To that end, the proportional relationships are carefully considered. The jar weighs an estimated fifty pounds empty and holds an estimated twelve gallons of water. At just over eight pounds to the gallon, the water weight of this jar&#39;s volumetric capacity is 100 pounds. 150 pounds is the approximate average weight of an adult human worldwide. Two thirds of human body weight is water.

&nbsp;

My interest in a reductive art grows from the silent service of my Quaker upbringing. Silence is a stripping away of distractions from the light within but it is not an absence of sound. Buckminster Fuller used to say that everything living is sunlight bound into matter. The bee&#39;s wax is a potent concentration of the nectar flowering plants produce to attract pollinators- the energy bound up in this wax is sunlight. According to Fuller this jar is a vessel of light. According to the Quakers, so am I.

&nbsp;

Jars exist as primary documents in the anthropological record. While organic sealants have been used for vessels in the past for both decorative and functional applications, beeswax is unusual especially in contemporary studio ceramics. One of the delightful discoveries during this jar&#39;s (and my own) journey to the gallery comes from the need to roll the jar for portions of the overland route. The jar gathered wax impressions where rocks and sticks touched it. It is a form of wax cylinder recording of its own journey. Like a wax cylinder, we cannot &ldquo;read&rdquo; the recording without appropriate audio equipment. The jar is the only physical record of its own journey. All other information is available only as long as this printed text, those I have told the story to, or I myself, the &ldquo;audio equipment&rdquo; if you will, remain alive. This exhibition is an annotated oral narrative.

&nbsp;

My present moment is the interface of how this jar came to be as you see it before you and of what its role will be after its useful life as a container is over. My work is its own most fleeting and least useful state.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Jordan Taylor

Hillsborough, NC

2010
